<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1913-11-07T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1913-11-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="542" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d542">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 422.11G93/698.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Minister</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Quito</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1913-11-07">
                                    <hi rend="italic">November 7, 1913</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>I informed the President of Ecuador to-day of the probable early
                            departure of Judge Miller for Ecuador, and suggested to him the
                            advisability executing a preliminary agreement between the Ecuadorean
                            Government and the Railway Company, specifically stating the points of
                            disagreement to be submitted to the Board of Arbitration, so that its
                            labors would be greatly expedited. He said that such an agreement would
                            not be necessary, as a memorandum agreement to the same effect had been
                            signed by the Secretary of State at Washington and the Ecuadorean
                            Minister during the past summer. No such paper is in the files of this
                                Legation.<note n="2" xml:id="d542fn2">But see Department’s August 13
                                to the American Minister.</note>
                        </p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Hartman</hi>.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>